      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-10-10T01:03:12Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Just \"[]string\" and \"time.Duration\". nil is a valid value for a slice (it just means it is empty). \n\nIn go it\u0027s atypical to use pointers to \"primitive\" types like slices and time.Duration (which is just int64 in disguise) to indicate optional values. Usually a zero value (nil for slices, 0 for duration, etc) is used for that purpose (assuming 0 doesn\u0027t have a meaning on its own in the context of the call). Pointers are more often used to represent \"optional\" structs (since to get a zero value for a struct involves a lot more typing than just \u0027nil\u0027 or \u00270\u0027).\n\nI think it would be sufficient just to document that if lifetime is zero, a default lifetime of 1h is used.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 186,
        "startChar": 97,
        "endLine": 186,
        "endChar": 141
      },
      "revId": "183177108876b22e37a1e6db0b5907fe6173bd69",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
